<div class="column middle">
  <br><h1>The Terminal</h1>
  <hr style='float: right; width:100%;'><br>
  
  <p>
  "We're all waiting for something."
  </p>
  <p>
  Subtlety is rare in Hollywood. Not so in The Terminal. The Terminal follows Viktor Navorski (Tom Hanks), who becomes stuck in a New York airport terminal after his country, Krakozhia ceases to exist following a coup. There is not much of a plot, but that's because there doesn't need to be one; instead, The Terminal tells a story, and all we as the audience want to know is what happens next. 
  </p>
  <p>
  Although Steven Spielberg can undoubtably deliver massive blockbusters, what he has done here feels like a much smaller, much more relatable piece of work. Almost all of us have spent some time at an airport, and even that in itself allows us to empath with Viktor's unfortunate predicament.
  </p>
  <p>
  "What can I do?"<br>
  "There's only one thing you can do here Viktor... Shop"
  </p>
  <p>
  There are genuinely funny moments scattered generously throughout, and what makes them all the better is that they just don't seem forced. Tom Hanks works effortlessly in this role, somehow perfectly capturing the naivë and confusion of a foreigner surrounded by the beauracracy of American border security. He also employs a thick accent (Bulgarian?) which somehow doesn't come off as ridiculous or unnatural. Honestly, he's just too good.
  </p>
  <p>
  Hank's naivëte is complemented by Frank Dixon (Stanley Tucci), the head officer of customs and the one who has to figure out what to do with Viktor. Various methods are employed by Dixon to get rid of him, but Viktor's naivë, luck, or nature means that he doesn't bite, so, for now, he stays. As the movie progresses, a love interest and a gradual unpacking of why Viktor is in New York in the first place both add to the story, all culminating in a sentimental but somewhat ambiguous conclusion. Overall, the Terminal is quaint, light and just generally enjoyable.
  </p>
  <p>
  7.2/10
  </p>
  <br>
